Josh Rocchi, 23 Feb 2024, 11:03 GMT

Good Morning,

We have provisioned your Smoothwall Monitor service and will be handing you over to our Support Team.

This means you can now go ahead with the installation and the links below are to be used as reference points when deploying Monitor within your environment:

Monitor Help Centre - KB Homepage

**Both the UNCL and ORGID are within Monitor > Organisation. Click Edit > Select Licence information.**


Your Safeguarding team may also find this link useful to understanding the platform, in particular the “Events” section which includes tables showing our justification for giving alerts specific levels: Using Monitor

If you need technical assistance, we would advise contacting your local IT support team or you can submit a request here: Submit a request – Knowledge Base

For all other questions please contact your Customer Success Manager at Smoothwall directly.

When appropriate please could you let them know a time that suits you and they’ll get this booked in.

On Mon, 5 Feb 2024 at 12:41, Wendy Harrington <w.harrington@ebor.academy>
<w.harrington@ebor.academy> wrote:

> Good afternoon
> Cyber-crime is regrettably on the increase and the education sector has
> not been spared from what can be devastating IT attacks. The consequence of
> such random, malicious activity can be considerable cost, both financially
> and in terms of hours or days spent restoring systems.
>
> Multi-factor authentication (MFA) is now commonplace as a defence,
> especially in online shopping and banking. Security fobs and, increasingly,
> mobile phone apps tend to be used to provide that additional layer of
> security. Put simply, using MFA on all our email accounts will ensure that
> whenever someone tries to use your email login from a different machine to
> your normal machine/telephone, the system will refuse access unless you
> authenticate the access.
>
> MFA will not completely stop the determined cyber attacker but by
> requiring additional information as an extra layer of protection, it is
> proving highly effective in minimising the attacks. An American security
> website suggests it can cut attacks by as much as 80-90%.
>
> Many governors will be aware that school staff all now have MFA on their
> google accounts. We now wish to extend this to all governors.  LGB Chairs
> have piloted this for us. Guidance on how to do this is attached.
>
> Any initial issues should be directed to help@vitalyork.com but please
> copy me in so I can be aware of any problems you are having. The Chairs I
> have spoken to have all managed it without an issue so I am hoping it will
> be straightforward for you

>

Hi!

Hope you are both okay and enjoyed half term.

I understand Claire Carr has already messaged you, but just to confirm Heather has broken her right thumb and it’s in pot. Similar to one of Claire’s sons but he has done his left thumb. Heather is right handed.
We go back on Monday 4/3 to see what the consultant says and hopefully it will have repair by then.

Yes, it was a hockey injury, she stopped the ball with her thumb which meant that her thumb was sandwiched between the stick and ball. She didn’t let it stop her though she continued for the last few minutes of the game which led to them scoring another goal. After the game Abi Brown gave her some snow from the side of the pitch to act as an ice pack before she started on the real ice packs.

I shouldn’t have said to her, well I’m pleased you aren’t playing 2s this week as Huddersfield tried wiping you out a few times last time! She got asked to play 1s and got a broken thumb! 🤦‍♀️ She played so well too. Hopefully it will repair quickly and she will be back in working order soon.

Kind regards,

Veronica

*From:* Groundwork UK - Tesco Stronger Starts Team <
mail@grantapplication.com>

*Subject:* *TESCO STRONGER STARTS OFFER CONFIRMATION - CONGRATULATIONS!*
*Reply-To:* Groundwork UK - Tesco Stronger Starts Team <
louise.malone@groundwork.org.uk>

DO NOT REPLY TO mailuk@ email address

REF NO: 107504

THIS IS YOUR REFERENCE NUMBER - PLEASE ENSURE THAT YOU QUOTE YOUR
ORGANISATION NAME AND YOUR REFERENCE NUMBER IN ALL EMAIL COMMUNICATIONS.


Dear Georgina,

Organisation name: Forest of Galtres Anglican Methodist Primary School
Project title: Forest School

Congratulations!

We are delighted to let you know that following the Tesco Stronger Starts
vote in your local Tesco stores, your project came First and has been
chosen by Tesco customers to receive a grant award of £1,500.00!


Voting was held at Tesco stores between 1st October 2023 to mid January
2024  and proved to be very successful with millions of votes being cast by
Tesco Customers across the UK.



What you need to do now

Please find attached a copy of your Grant Offer letter, which details
important information you will need to read carefully in order to formally
accept your offer of grant.  Before we can begin to make payments you will
need to accept our Grant Offer and Terms and Conditions, and correctly
complete our due diligence requirements.


Your grant will be paid in two instalments. The first instalment will be
75%  and the final 25% will be paid upon successful submission of your
completion report.

You must complete and submit all acceptance forms by close of play on
Friday 15th March 2024, or your grant offer will be withdrawn.  Please be
aware that NO PAYMENT will be released until we receive the CORRECT
information from you.  You are required to complete this process through a
secure web portal.

Special Conditions


All projects must be completed within 12 months of receiving this offer
email.

The link to log into your online account is as follows:
www.grantrequest.co.uk/SID_26/?SA=AM

(Please copy the above link and then paste it into the address bar in your
Internet Browser, as clicking the link might not work for you. )

Please use the username (the email address shown here:-
georginaharrison13@hotmail.com) and the password you used when creating
your account to login (or the latest one if this has changed since your
account was created).

If you have forgotten your password, you can request a new one by visiting
the login page above.  If the email address linked to your account needs to
be amended, please email tescostrongerstarts@groundwork.org.uk with the new
email address that your account needs to be linked to.

Should you have any queries with any step of the process, please contact us
at tescostrongerstarts@groundwork.org.uk.

We would also like to take this opportunity to draw your attention to the
clause within the Terms and Conditions:
6.4 We will fill in a Project Completion Report, within the 12 months of
the Grant Offer date for this project.  We will use the form you send us.
We understand that the grant is finished only after we have completed this
report to your satisfaction and you have received to your satisfaction the
evidence of expenditure you have requested for the period of the Grant
Agreement.  Failure to complete the project and provide a satisfactory
completion report, within 12 months of the Grant Offer letter is deemed a
failure to comply with these terms and conditions and may result in
repayment of funds awarded.

Promoting the results and your project

You can find communications guidance and associated press release template
by following the link in your offer letter.  This will help you to promote
your project online and to your local media.

Thank you to everyone who has helped to promote projects and Tesco Stronger
Starts so far. Please follow the links in your offer letter for guidance on
how you can promote the results of the vote and how any associated
promotional activity will be carried out.

https://tescostrongerstarts.org.uk/communications-guidance-uk/

Congratulations from us all again and we look forward to working with you
and seeing your completed project and the difference that it will make in
your local community.

Kind Regards,

Tesco Stronger Starts Team - Groundwork UK

---------- Forwarded message ---------
From: Safeguarding in Education <safeguardingineducation@eastriding.gov.uk>
Date: Tue, 20 Feb 2024 at 14:46
Subject: Malicious Emails **** PLEASE READ IMPORTANT ******
To: Safeguarding in Education <safeguardingineducation@eastriding.gov.uk>


Please read below information from Humberside Police.  We have shared this
with the Schools ICT
If you have an in-house IT Team, please share immediately
Obviously, do not click on any links and take great care if you receive
any  incoming unrecognised email that could be part of this.


Good Afternoon,



I am the detective sergeant in Humberside Police cyber Crime Department.



I have today been informed that several East Riding Schools have received
what on the face of it is a potential malicious email from colleagues,
stating that documents/file have been shared with the recipient  via
Microsoft 365.



I am advised that the majority of recipients happen to be safeguarding
leads for the respective schools.



With that in mind I wish to make you aware of the current increase of
reports over the past couple of days and to alert you and your teams of the
potential threat of unsolicited emails and malicious links.



I am yet to formally identify if they links are malicious or genuine,
however I am taking this precautionary step to notify you for further
dissemination across the education authority for East Riding.  If you have
a like contact in the Hull area whom I can forward this to it would be
appreciated.



I will not post the link here as to authenticate this message but ask that
you visit the NCSC website for the governments advice for phishing
campaigns by threat actors and subsequent threats you may encounter in the
Cyber Landscape.



I am available to take any questions relating to this via telephone or
email.



*Leigh Burgin*

From "Nick Porter" <team.wfal@wefindanylearner.com>: Hello,

We are absolutely thrilled to announce that we are offering not one, not two, but THREE of our most popular online courses completely free of charge! Yes, you heard that right - FREE!

But don't wait too long to register your interest, as spots are filling up fast. This is an incredible opportunity that you won't want to miss out on. You can easily sign up on our website at www.wefindanylearner.com/book-online/ or by contacting our team at 01226 958 888.

All you need to do is meet a few simple criteria, including being at least 19 years old by August 31st, 2022, residing in England, and not currently enrolled in an apprenticeship program.

Enrol today and let's make a difference together!

Counselling Skills Level 2
Many people find it helpful to seek counselling at some point in their lives, and a counsellor can provide support for people in all sorts of situations. If you’re interested in supporting people to improve their personal well-being, this course will provide you with the correct understanding, knowledge and skills to do that. You’ll learn about core counselling skills and how to use them in a counselling relationship. You will also be taught about counselling theory and the ethical framework that informs how counsellors use their skills.

Mental Health First Aid Level 2
It’s important that employers are transparent and open about mental health issues, and this qualification builds an understanding of mental health problems and the support available to colleagues. Increasing the understanding of the mental health of staff at all levels builds a culture of care and support.

Understanding Autism Level 2
This course will give you an understanding of autism and the principles of supporting individuals with autism. You will look at the person-centred approach and the influence that positive communication methods can have and will gain an understanding of how individuals with autism can be supported to live healthy and fulfilled lives.

Subject: New Starter - Y8 Kacie Baines

Hi All,

Kacie will be joining us from Monday 19th February, she is coming on an OSD trial from JoRo.

Background: Kacie has poor attendance at JoRo which is the reason for her trial, she attended 35% in Y7 and 1% in Y8. This is an opportunity for a fresh start. There are no behaviour concerns around Kacie she is suffering from social anxiety.
Due to her poor attendance, we have limited knowledge of her current levels, however she has a non-verbal CATS of 75. Gareth and the team will be assessing her as soon as she starts with us so we have a better understanding of how to support her. For this reason she has been placed into the Y8 nurture group.

Kacie attended primary school with a few of students, Haxby Road. She currently knows Lauren N and Brie.

We will be keeping a close eye as she settles.

Any concerns please let me know

Thanks

Kim

Any new staff members of visitors can be added to the ParentPay system
using MIS Sync. Currently, any  changes to the staff and visitor details
(such as changing a name due to marriage) will need to be completed by the
ParentPay support team.

*WARNING: *When adding new staff or visitors, you must also include any
staff or visitors who are already on the ParentPay system in the upload.

If only the new members of staff or visitor records are processed in the
upload, any records already held on the ParentPay system will be
overwritten and archived. This will then prevent current staff or visitors
from accessing their ParentPay account.

   1. Open the *MIS Sync* program and log in
   2. Select *Staff > Manage data* or* Visitors > Manage data*
   3. Select *Import*.
   [image: mceclip0.png]
   4. You will receive a message stating how many existing records have
   been imported
   [image: mceclip1.png]
   5. Select *OK*. The *Manage tab* will be opened, and all staff or
   visitors currently held in the ParentPay system will be displayed. You can
   then add, amend, or delete records here
   6. Select *Save*
   7. The upload tab will open. Ensure the *Export to* option is set
to *ParentPay
   Web Site*, and select *Export*
   [image: mceclip2.png]
   8. The data upload will then process. If it is successful, a message
   reading *Succeeded* will be displayed.
   [image: mceclip3.png]
   9. These records will have been sent directly to your ParentPay website
   and the staff/visitor details can be viewed in *People > Pupils and
   Staff* by changing the *Group 1* drop down menu to Staff or Visitors.
   10. Activation letters can then be created for the staff members or
   visitors added to the site.

Hello Jeanine

This means you will need to locate your SIMS.net folder so MIS Sync can
extract the details from SIMS to upload the pupil data. You would need to
do the following on MIS Sync:
1. Click on Tools > settings > SIMS

2. Where it says MIS username MIS Password, you need to enter in your SIMS
username and password and NOT the ParentPay username/password

3. Once entered, click the yellow folder and it locate the SIMS.net folder
(this should open and try to locate your SIMS.net folder location.

4. Once you see the SIMS.net folder,  click Test these Settings which
should say, connection test was successful, then Save.

5. Now close MIS Sync, log back in then click on Pupils > Auto update.

If you still get the same error could not locate SIMS with your current
settings, this means that you have not selected the correct SIMS.net
location. This would be something you would need to speak to your IT team
about.
In order to use MIS Sync and SIMS, the user needs to have the following in
SIMS:
3rd party reporting rights in SIMS and their access must be admin or higher
which could be the reason they cannot locate the SIMS.net folder.

Kind regards



Lucy Gajb
Customer Support Advisor

On 05/02/2024 12:41, Wendy Harrington wrote:

Good afternoon
Cyber-crime is regrettably on the increase and the education sector has not
been spared from what can be devastating IT attacks. The consequence of
such random, malicious activity can be considerable cost, both financially
and in terms of hours or days spent restoring systems.

Multi-factor authentication (MFA) is now commonplace as a defence,
especially in online shopping and banking. Security fobs and, increasingly,
mobile phone apps tend to be used to provide that additional layer of
security. Put simply, using MFA on all our email accounts will ensure that
whenever someone tries to use your email login from a different machine to
your normal machine/telephone, the system will refuse access unless you
authenticate the access.

MFA will not completely stop the determined cyber attacker but by requiring
additional information as an extra layer of protection, it is proving
highly effective in minimising the attacks. An American security website
suggests it can cut attacks by as much as 80-90%.

Many governors will be aware that school staff all now have MFA on their
google accounts. We now wish to extend this to all governors.  LGB Chairs
have piloted this for us. Guidance on how to do this is attached.

Any initial issues should be directed to help@vitalyork.com but please copy
me in so I can be aware of any problems you are having. The Chairs I have
spoken to have all managed it without an issue so I am hoping it will be
straightforward for you

Wendy

From: Adobe <Adobe@info.adobe.com>

You don't often get email from adobe@info.adobe.com<mailto:adobe@info.adobe.com>. Learn why this is important<https://aka.ms/LearnAboutSenderIdentification>
Adobe is discontinuing the Creative Cloud Synced files feature for business customers beginning 1 October 2024.  ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌  ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌  ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌  ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌
[Adobe]
Dear Creative Cloud Administrator,

Adobe is modernising the Creative Cloud storage experience and
will begin discontinuing Creative Cloud Synced files for business customers under Creative Cloud for Teams and Creative Cloud for Enterprise plans.

Creative Cloud Synced files is general-purpose cloud storage and sync that consists of a local folder on users’ device(s), a background process that creates synchronised copies of those files in Creative Cloud storage and file/folder sharing. This service is separate from Adobe Cloud Documents, Cloud Libraries, Lightroom cloud storage and Frame.io cloud storage – none of which are impacted by this change.

Beginning 1 February 2024

Users will no longer be able to share files or folders from Creative Cloud Synced files with new users outside of your organisation, sharing will continue to work within your organisation until 1 October 2024.

Beginning 1 October 2024

We will begin discontinuing the Creative Cloud content synchronisation process, as well as synced file and folder sharing, and permanently delete the cloud-based copies of files for business customers and their end users.

Assets in the local Creative Cloud Files folder on user devices will no longer be synchronised with Creative Cloud storage. User files will remain intact in their local Creative Cloud Files folder.

Folders and assets previously shared from Creative Cloud Synced files will no longer be accessible to others including inside your organisation as well as externally.

Recommended actions:

It is recommended that you inform the users in your organisation about this upcoming change. In addition, make sure that your organisation's assets are safely backed up either locally, to a separate Adobe-supported cloud storage solution or to third-party cloud storage. Adobe will not be sending out notifications regarding this change directly to your organisation's users.
You can read more about this change and managing your files here<https://adobeint-mid-prod13-t.adobe-campaign.com/r/?id=haa06a101,d481903f,8003e1cc>.

Adobe’s Customer Support organisation is available to answer any questions.

Dear all,
At OLQM, we currently have at least 15 chromebooks with damaged batteries
that have expanded meaning they can no longer be used. I have asked all
teachers to check their chromebook trolleys in case there are others.

I'm concerned about this from a safety point of view, and so have removed
these from classrooms. It is also having an impact on our ability to
deliver our curriculum - computing and other subjects - as some classes
have gone from a 1:1 ratio to 1:4.

I believe this has been logged by a colleague with both Vital and NPCAT,
but I'm unsure whose responsibility or jurisdiction this would be.

Any advice would be much appreciated on how we can move this forward to get
these chromebooks back working again.

*Kerry - the chromebooks are currently on my office desk. Is there anywhere
safer we can put them in the meantime?*


Thanks,

that may affect email traffic within your Docebo platform.



Google and Yahoo have updated their guidelines for sending communications
to their email addresses. These changes aim to improve the overall security
and reliability of their email services. However, these changes may impact
how emails from SaaS providers like Docebo are received by users.



Docebo already covers these requirements if SPF and DKIM are properly
configured in the platform. If you have not completely configured your
platform email settings and you are using the “Notification” or
“Newsletter” features of Docebo to send communications to learners with “
gmail.com” or “yahoo.com” email addresses, these changes could affect your
platform.



To ensure your communications are not identified as spam by Google or
Yahoo, there are certain steps you may need to take. These steps, and the
full details behind these changes, can be found in the community post
<https://cdQDg04.na1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/DI+113/cdQDg04/VW44kz1SvzV5W8vW7_638RCPGW2jjqKJ58Z9-6MJvQmj5kBVqW5BWr2F6lZ3n3W4TnGf844bFNpW362W5y2XrHD0W3SGL0w4gWPkcN97VXcxr06ZxN3zZt5K7MmB-N94vRCZVyTv4W2Sc0WT2Nm7q8W3dfNtN2Z8B5WW2r2FBW343wwTW5pSvnQ9fv7Z2W63GS5-8VZj7GW90WKpq2RDK0mW3gSzvm2QTy-SW9k4TtT4vdG85W4tJ_F25lYgqwVnNbcr8JF6KFW9fZfpW7RL_PWW4JqgwD8PHHylW1hl5ZM6HF45ZW9bhzjH3C9HR6W4l1F7Q5P0f_xW6PqDjf40HX70W7QYqdl5pvmrNW7_Z8Nx6SYZwrW7mR-Xm5PJhnFW8dMPxx5v0WjTW1NPsdY7YG6FJW62zhSl53GbP7W9dqZvJ1rs4QzW8BVQN631FR4bW8SBbb78gTZHrW1slXs87FC2vvVGmW0B6y51LlW12jvL37WLdtFf3hzGXz04>

Hi James
I am getting increasingly frustrated with attaching files which I have edited. It happens with the quiz, with my bulletin etc.
What happens is I finish my bulletin, I then go on to emails and attach the bulleting as a copy (not a link). Then I open it and see some of the formatting has changed. I then remove the attachment. login - and access to her docs etc - for Jonathan.

without breaking things though! Call me if clarification needed?

[required] Title: Re: FAM - Off site direction - Lilly Anne Kinder
Description:
Hi,

Please see notes from a meeting with Lillyanne Kinder, gran, Gaynor, and
Head of Year at Millthorpe below.

*Actions from meeting*:

- Lillyanne will be starting on Monday.
- *Katie *- please can this be added to SIMS?
- *Alexis*, please can she be issued a timetable? I think she may have to
go into A band based on the space we have - if there is space however, D
band, French, would be better for relationships and language. Please can
she also be factored into Options? She thinks she wants to do
Graphics/Child Development.
- *Simone* - she will have trousers/shirt/shoes hopefully. We will provide
a tie/jumper and she will need a PE kit too. Would you be able to put some
things aside for her and we can pass on? She is PP/FSM.
- *Yr team* - she has not yet had a tour/planner/TT etc so I have asked Rob
if he can spend Monday P1 setting her up, showing her key areas and doing
any troubleshooting. Gran wants to bring her in on her first day and will
bring her in for 8:30am.
- *IT *- once she is on SIMS please can she have a Google classroom/IT
login?


*Information about Lillyanne:*

- Must be *Lillyanne*, not Lilly - she gets annoyed at being called this.
- Difficult home life. Mum disabled and bed/wheelchair bound. Mum is very
volatile and can be aggressive on the phone. HofY advised call gran
wherever possible, and mum in afternoons after pain meds have kicked in if
we have to.
- Lillyanne moved in with gran 3 weeks ago and moving forward will be with
gran during the weekdays. HofY said she is like a different child since
this happened. Gran is really desperate to support and wants to work with
us.
- Lillyanne is a young carer of gran at home.
- Lillyanne is youngest of 6. Matty (Y11) was with her and mum. He also
struggles and accessing alternate provision. Lillyanne loves Matty and
affected if anything goes wrong with him. 4 older siblings (youngest age
20) as well as Matty, all moved out of home.
- She is on free school meals
- Lillyanne finds it difficult to make friends, but already knows and is
friendly with Karla Horrocks, Ellie Mason and Lily-May Hartley at AHS.
- Studies French atm but we talked about there potentially not being room
in this band.
- Likes English, Food tech, Maths. Dislikes drama but won't be on her TT
here - spoke about English enrichment not involving drama currently.
- No sports/hobbies she could point to but likes hair/makeup
- Lillyanne articulated that her main issues have stemmed from associating
with negative influences, messing around, lates.
- After Lillyanne left, HofY disclosed the main reason for suspensions is
verbal abuse of staff. She stressed that Lillyanne must be left alone to
cool off if there are issues - when staff try to intervene she blows up.
Other reason is walking out of Reflection which is an instant suspension at
Millthorpe. Terrible language used which is modelled by mum at home.
- Low self-confidence - has been part of a workshop to address this at
Millthorpe
- Needs to be in control of her work/perfectionist. Has good effort scores
on reports. Will highlight everything, tear out pages and rewrite them if
they aren't neat enough. Wants to do well.
- Has attachment issues and may try to hug staff if she forms a connection;
has attempted this with HofY at Millthorpe. HofY described her 'just
wanting another parent'
- No SEN, but weak due to gaps in learning primarily.
- No specialist provision at Millthorpe beyond support from yr team.

accessing the RWInc portal? Links can be copied to the Google Classroom,

Sara

Hi Sara,

Thanks so much for your email and for raising SH being in class on a Mon +
Tues. As Mrs Martin covers EYFS these days it would be down to an adult
setting up (on their own login) the portal as when the children log in on
theirs the portal does not load the videos. I have spoken to vital and
Corinne about this before and it seems that the portal only works if an
adult logs in first. Would this be tricky in regards to GDPR?

Happy to accommodate and in the best interests of SH help to make this
work. Mrs Martin is happy to set up a chrome book on a Monday and Tuesday
with the portal open but there are concerns that she might access something
unintentionally.

Many thanks,

Georgina

[required] Title: Dye sublimation printer- opportunity to enhance the quality of DT products and a wider school use to raise funds or personalise for new students.
Description:
We have a non functioning dye-sublimation printer (photo enclosed). This
would allow us to print onto a wide range of surfaces with a polymer
content, so any surface that has a plastic finish. Examples; coasters,
t-shirts, baseball hats, drinks bottles etc.
The process works as follows:-

1) Print image using dye-sublimation paper (our printer is not currently
working)
2) Place image on object to receive print
3) Use heat to seal the image onto the object (we already have a specialist
heat press to do this and all the fittings to print onto bottles, mugs,
hats, t shirts etc)

Link below to some products that can be printed on (not endless) just from
one supplier

https://www.techsoft.co.uk/products/image-transfer-accessories/blanks-products-ready-for-sublimation-only


Unfortunately the printer does not at the moment function, I am not sure
why as it has been like that before I arrived here.

I want to get it working or if not look at replacing it.

https://www.techsoft.co.uk/products/image-transfer/sublimation

Just a few ideas to use this dye sublimation process in school


   1. Printing personalised images onto fabric at KS3 for Textiles
   2. Printing onto surfaces to enhance the quality of products for KS4
   3. Raising funds by making personalised items
   4. Year 8 students creating in house designed items for new students or
   September intake.
   5. Setting up mini-enterprise businesses for Business.


Can IT support first please have a look at the printer, to see if it can be
maintained or repaired. We can then go from there. The printer is in G2 by
the whiteboard.




Thanks

Ed

[required] Title: Chrome books not charged / missing / real mess
Description:
Hi Jimmy.

The chrome book situation is a real issue - it has hugely been affecting
lessons and learning time. I yesterday tried to do a coursework lesson with
my GCSE year 10s and after 30 minutes I finally got the whole class on a
chrome book to start on their coursework. Half were not working, out of

[required] Title: Single sign on from iTrent to Staff Learning Hub
Description:
Hello

I know that you are working on getting SSO into each school but wondering
if the following information would help with getting the link from iTrent
to Staff Learning Hub working?

If Rob remembers he attended the initial LMS IT infrastructure call on 27th
April this year with MHR.

Thank you

*SSO*

Should you wish to use Single Sign-on as an authentication method for the
LMS, your protocol of choice is likely to be SAML which has already been
activated on the platform. Bear in mind we are waiting on iTrent user
provisioning/maintenance to be in place before we can action this phase of
the LMS project (SSO), please just find the information below regarding
configuring SSO for when the time is suitable.

   - *SAML 2.0 protocol* (intro article
   <https://www.docebo.com/knowledge-base/introduction-to-docebo-for-saml/>
   , standard config article <https://www.docebo.com/knowledge-base/saml/>)
   - supports both SSO and user provisioning and works for Microsoft ADFS (ADFS
   article
   <https://www.docebo.com/knowledge-base/enabling-sso-docebo-microsoft-adfs/>),
   Microsoft Azure AD B2B (though the Azure AD Connect optional module is
   needed), Microsoft Azure AD B2C, Okta and many other IdPs. – *Note it’s
   likely you’ll be using the standard configuration option*


-- 
*Louise Jackson*
Learning and Development Administrator
L3 Business Administrator Apprenticeship Tutor
